If you have a Magento powered store with larger number of products in it, chances are you are using the so called <strong>Flat Catalog Product</strong> and <strong>Flat Catalog Category</strong> options, found under <strong>System > Configuration > Catalog > Catalog > Frontend</strong>.

In such cases, every now and then you might see a "<em>One or more of the Indexes are not up to date: Product Attributes, Product Prices, Catalog URL Rewrites, Product Flat Data, Category Products, Catalog Search Index, Stock Status, Tag Aggregation Data. Click here to go to Index Management and rebuild required indexes.</em>" message jumping out in admin.<!--more-->

Usual reaction for store owners is to simply go under <strong>System > Index Management > Select All > Reindex Data > Submit</strong>. The problem here is that if you have a store with large number of products, lets say 10k, 50k or more, then doing this is an extremely bad idea. Reindexing can take up from a few minutes to even few hours, depending how your PHP execution time is configured.

In such cases as well as in cases of possible custom import scripts you might want to switch this task to cron triggered script that fires at specific time of the day. Below is an example of programmatically reindex indexers, but only those that need to be reindexed.

<pre><code class="language-php">
$indexers = Mage::getSingleton('index/indexer')
					->getProcessesCollection();

foreach ($indexers as $indexer) {
	if ($indexer->getStatus() == Mage_Index_Model_Process::STATUS_REQUIRE_REINDEX) {
		$indexer->reindexEverything();
	}
}
</code></pre>

Hope this helps.

Creating the "Add to Cart" button for a bundle product type within your custom theme is a bit more challenging then it seems at first. That is, if you want the button to actually directly add the bundle product to cart if clicked. This goes for every composite product, or the one with custom options. Reason is that Magento does not know what options / items within that product you wish to add to cart. Ideally, it would allow us to add composite products for options whose defaults we have set, but it does not. So how do we bypass this?<!--more-->

This article goes on by demonstrating how to add bundle product to cart via single link, but only if its Bundle Items have been set to defaults, like shown in the image below.

[caption id="attachment_322" align="alignnone" width="478"]<a href="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/magento-bundle-product-edit.png"><img src="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/magento-bundle-product-edit-478x1024.png" alt="Magento Bundle Product - Bundle Items" width="478" height="1024" class="size-large wp-image-322" /></a> Magento Bundle Product - Bundle Items[/caption]

This would produce the following result on the frontend.

[caption id="attachment_323" align="alignnone" width="559"]<a href="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/magento-bundle-product-view.png"><img src="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/magento-bundle-product-view-559x1024.png" alt="Magento Bundle Product - Product View Page" width="559" height="1024" class="size-large wp-image-323" /></a> Magento Bundle Product - Product View Page[/caption]

Now if you use your browser toolbar (Firebug, etc.) or tool like Charles Web Debugging Proxy and record the action of actually clicking the "Add to Cart" button on the product view page, you would see the parameters that get sent to the addAction() of the Mage_Checkout_CartController class, as shown below.

[caption id="attachment_324" align="alignnone" width="604"]<a href="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/bundle-add-to-cart-POST-params.png"><img src="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/bundle-add-to-cart-POST-params-1024x640.png" alt="Magento Bundle Product - Add to Cart params" width="604" height="377" class="size-large wp-image-324" /></a> Magento Bundle Product - Add to Cart params[/caption]

Which results in following being added to cart.

[caption id="attachment_325" align="alignnone" width="604"]<a href="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/bundle-cart.png"><img src="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/bundle-cart-793x1024.png" alt="Magento Bundle Product - Cart" width="604" height="779" class="size-large wp-image-325" /></a> Magento Bundle Product - Cart[/caption]

As you can see from the screens below, the HTTP method used to submit product to cart was POST. However, if you trace the code within addAction() and further you will see no forcing of POST method. Meaning you can just as easily submit your params via HTTP GET method, as long as you are able to reproduce them.

Following is a code snippet which works on following cases:

<ul>
	<li>you are only using select option types for Bundle Items</li>
	<li>you are only using checkbox option types for Bundle Items</li>
	<li>you are only using radio option types for Bundle Items</li>
	<li>you are only using select multiselect types for Bundle Items</li>
	<li>you are only using combination of mentioned option types for Bundle Items</li>
	<li>you set the default value and qty for every Bundle Item option</li> 
</ul>

This code snippet was tested on Magento 1.8.1.0. Code placed within your theme, controller, model, helper or other file (after Magento session has been initialised) should produce a valid URL link which you can place as a href attribute of some custom button, or try copy-pasting directly into browser for testing.

<pre><code class="language-php">/***************/
$qty = 3;
$productId = 165;
/***************/

$product = Mage::getModel('catalog/product');
$product->load($productId);

$resource = Mage::getSingleton('core/resource');
$readConnection = $resource->getConnection('core_read');

$query = sprintf('SELECT option_id, type FROM %s WHERE option_id IN (SELECT DISTINCT option_id FROM %s WHERE parent_product_id = %s);', $resource->getTableName('catalog_product_bundle_option'), $resource->getTableName('catalog_product_bundle_selection'), (int)$product->getId());
$optionTypes = $readConnection->fetchAll($query);
$optionTypesKV = array();

foreach ($optionTypes as $optionType) {
    $optionTypesKV[$optionType['option_id']] = $optionType['type'];
}

$query = sprintf('SELECT selection_id, option_id, selection_qty FROM %s WHERE parent_product_id = %s AND is_default = 1;', $resource->getTableName('catalog_product_bundle_selection'), (int)$product->getId());
$optionSelections = $readConnection->fetchAll($query);

$options = '';

foreach ($optionSelections as $optionSelection) {

    if (in_array($optionTypesKV[$optionSelection['option_id']], array('radio', 'select'))) {
        $options .= sprintf('bundle_option[%s]=%s&', $optionSelection['option_id'], $optionSelection['selection_id']);
    }

    if (in_array($optionTypesKV[$optionSelection['option_id']], array('checkbox', 'multi'))) {
        $options .= sprintf('bundle_option[%s][]=%s&', $optionSelection['option_id'], $optionSelection['selection_id']);
    }

}

$add2CartUrl = Mage::helper('checkout/cart')->getAddUrl($product, array('_query'=>$options, 'qty'=>$qty) );

echo $add2CartUrl;</code></pre>

I am using two raw database connections here, bypassing possible models and collections for fetching the same thing. Not exactly the best Magento practice but gets the job done, and does so fast.

Please note that you have to run this code within the session (after it has been initialised), due to the <em>form_key</em> parameter, or else your generated form_key parameter wont be the same one during the addAction() method check. Meaning if you run it within your theme, model, block, helper and other classes you should be OK.

Hope someone finds it useful.

Magento layered navigation is considered to be one of the most trickiest part to customize. In this article I will show you how to create your own custom filter for it.

<?php

class Mage_Catalog_Block_Layer_Filter_Foggy extends Mage_Catalog_Block_Layer_Filter_Abstract
{
    public function __construct()
    {
        parent::__construct();

        $this->_filterModelName = 'catalog/layer_filter_foggy';
    }
}


