Wouldn't it be nice for Magento search to redirect your customer automatically to a product page for every search that results in a single product being found? Sure it would! Imagine a scenario where your customer is using quick search, or even advanced search facility in Magento and the search returns a single product. Why trouble a customer for that extra one click to go to a product page when you can do it programmatically, that is from code.<!--more-->

Idea is pretty simple; we observe the following two events and simply attach observe to them which will redirect to product page in case of one found result:
<ul>
<li><em>controller_action_postdispatch_catalogsearch_result_index</em> in charge of Quick Search results</li>
<li><em>controller_action_postdispatch_catalogsearch_advanced_result</em> in charge of Advanced Search results</li>
</ul>

Attaching observer to these events is pretty easy; simply define one in your extension config.xml file as shown below.

<pre><code class="language-php"><frontend>
        <events>
            <controller_action_postdispatch_catalogsearch_result_index>
                <observers>
                    <foggyline_singleresultsearch_1>
                        <class>foggyline_singleresultsearch/observer</class>
                        <method>redirectToProductPage</method>
                    </foggyline_singleresultsearch_1>
                </observers>
            </controller_action_postdispatch_catalogsearch_result_index>
            <controller_action_postdispatch_catalogsearch_advanced_result>
                <observers>
                    <foggyline_singleresultsearch_2>
                        <class>foggyline_singleresultsearch/observer</class>
                        <method>redirectToProductPage</method>
                    </foggyline_singleresultsearch_2>
                </observers>
            </controller_action_postdispatch_catalogsearch_advanced_result>            
        </events>
    </frontend></code></pre>

Once the observer has been defined, you can add the actual logic to it, as shown below.

<pre><code class="language-php">    public function redirectToProductPage($observer) {

        if (!$this->_helper->isModuleOutputEnabled()) {
            return;
        }

        $result = Mage::app()->getLayout()->getBlock('search_result_list');
        $products = $result->getLoadedProductCollection();

        if (1 === (int) $products->getSize()) {
            if ($this->_helper->getMsgShow()) {
                $msg = $this->_helper->getMsgLabel();
                $msg = str_replace('[[PRODUCT]]', $products->getFirstItem()->getName(), $msg);

                $message = Mage::getSingleton('core/message')
                        ->{$this->_helper->getMsgType()}($msg);

                Mage::getSingleton('core/session')->addMessage($message);
            }

            if ('catalogsearch_result_index' === $observer->getControllerAction()->getFullActionName()) {
                $params = $observer->getControllerAction()->getRequest()->getParams();
                header(sprintf('Location: %s?%s', $products->getFirstItem()->getProductUrl(), http_build_query($params)));
                exit;
            } else {
                header('Location: '.$products->getFirstItem()->getProductUrl());
                exit;
            }
        }
    }</code></pre>

The only real challenge in this code snippet was figuring out how to grab a search result collection. So how do we figure that one? Well, its easy. First we need to remind ourselves that we are observing <em>postdispatch</em> type of controller event. This means that all those load <em>$this->loadLayout();</em> and <em>$this->renderLayout();</em> method calls from our controller have been executed, meaning blocks that hold the actual search result collection that is suppose to be passed to template files have been run/initiated. 

All we have to figure out is how to grab such a block and extract the searched results collection from it. In this case, the magic is within block named <em>search_result_list</em>; which we can reference through layout instance. Once we get the reference to collection, we can do a size count on it to figure out if it has only one product in it. If only one product is found, grab it from collection, read its product url and redirect to product page.

This post merely describes the concept; it lacks details for you to construct fully working example. However, I wrote a fully working <a href="https://github.com/ajzele/Foggyline_SingleResultSearch">Foggyline_SingleResultSearch</a> extension, whith configuraton options support that you can download from GitHub <a href="https://github.com/ajzele/Foggyline_SingleResultSearch">here</a>.

Screen below show the configuration are with options supported by extension. Configuration options can be found at <em>System > Configuration > Catalog > Foggyline | Single Result Search</em>.

