Depending on your business needs and processes you might have a need to store your customer credit card(s) info for later processing. Storing sensitive data like this on your own servers can turn out to be a real security / PCI compliance nightmare. Personally I am against any such form of storing credit card info on a non-cardholder systems, but this article is not about my personal bias, its about technical capabilities at your disposal.

<strong>The Vault API provides a secure way to store customer credit cards.</strong><!--more-->

Using Vault API is simple; you specify the card details in a call to the Vault API and as a result you get back the card ID. You then store this card ID within your system for later use. Later when you need to fetch back the full credit card info from the vault you make another API call passing it the card ID.

<strong>Vault API is based on REST requests.</strong>

The first step towards making Vault API calls is to create the PayPal app. I will demonstrate these example API calls on my PayPal developer account. In order to make the PayPal REST app, you need to login to https://developer.paypal.com/webapps/developer/applications/myapps and click on the "Create App" button. This opens up the screen like the one shown below, where I called my app "Vaulty".

[caption id="attachment_522" align="alignnone" width="944"]<a href="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/snap_2014.04.30_10h09m00s_002_.png"><img src="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/snap_2014.04.30_10h09m00s_002_.png" alt="PayPal Vault REST app" width="944" height="654" class="size-full wp-image-522" /></a> PayPal Vault REST app[/caption]

This gives you several important pieces of data, two of which interest us the most for the moment: 
<ul>
<li>Client ID: Ab0n2BDk4pHXLwu0UA4Zy5z6B0Ro6XmZFdupTbXjTGjqk_jv9vu80awY9IdU</li>
<li>Secret: EHxEvBDwNgxy8TKeCaaVeJKvckXGTBBeGijk8xVn5SBelx3YaMEmI4PJZM8V</li>
</ul>

<em>Note, the above Client ID and Secret are simply example values, my REST app will be deleted from my sandbox after this article so these values wont work for you, you need to create your own REST app in your own PayPal sandbox.</em>

PayPal has a nice set of API's out there on GiHub that you can use to execute the API calls:
<ul>
