<h3><i>Look up</i> a stored credit card</h3>

Once we have stored credit card info in the PayPal Vault and store its ID, we can later always request the full credit card info from Vault just by executing the following code.

<pre><code class="language-php">if ($access_token AND $cardId) {

	$ch = curl_init();

	$options = array(
		CURLOPT_URL => 'https://api.sandbox.paypal.com/v1/vault/credit-card/'.$cardId,
		CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER => 1,
		CURLOPT_HTTPHEADER => array(
			'Accept: application/json',
			'Content-Type: application/json',
			'Authorization: Bearer '.$access_token,
		),
		CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYPEER => false, /* security issue... OK for testing :P */
	);

	curl_setopt_array($ch, $options);

	$response = curl_exec($ch);
	$curl_errno = curl_errno($ch);
	$curl_error = curl_error($ch);
	curl_close($ch);

	if ($curl_errno > 0) {
		echo sprintf('cURL Error #%s : %s.', $curl_errno, $curl_error);
	} else {
		$cardInfo = json_decode($response);		
	}
}
</code></pre>

The response object here is the same as with the previous API call where we where creating the entry for the first time.

<h3><i>Delete</i> a stored credit card</h3>

Finally, to circle up the process we take a look at the delete action. Delete API call is basically the same API call (to the same URL) with just a changed HTTP request method (DELETE) as shown below.

<pre><code class="language-php">if ($access_token AND $cardId) {	

	$ch = curl_init();

	$options = array(
