Besides using the official API, there is one more direct method you can use to "integrate" Magento with other platforms or your custom code. Its almost as simple as just including the Mage.php file and triggering Mage::app() call. However, in order to get it really working, there is one important thing to keep in mind, which is sessions. You need to be able to access Magento sessions from outside Magento. First step in doing so is setting up the <strong>System > Configuration > General > Web > Session Cookie Management</strong> options.<!--more-->

Before we do so, let me just emphasize that in my case I had an integration where Magento is run from within a folder called <strong>shop</strong> and I was accessing it from Drupal platfrom which was in the root folder hosting the "shop" folder.

Thus, in my case I needed to set the <strong>Cookie Path</strong> value to "/" in order to be able to access it from the root of site, from Drupal.

<a href="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/snap_2014.05.30_08h21m39s_036_.png"><img src="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/snap_2014.05.30_08h21m39s_036_.png" alt="snap_2014.05.30_08h21m39s_036_" width="867" height="461" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-637" /></a>

Once you change the values under the <strong>Session Cookie Management</strong>, be sure to delete all of the sessions (var/session/*), cache (var/cashe/*) under Magento var folder and your browser cookies.

<h3>Session object</h3>

Why do we need session object? We need it at least to pull the cart status and other important stuff you get to access when logged in, you know "<em>X items in cart</em>", etc.

If you login to your Magento as a customer, you should be able to access the session object from the root (above the /shop/) folder like shown in the code below.

<pre><code class="language-php">require_once './shop/app/Mage.php';

umask(0);

Mage::init();

Mage::getSingleton('core/session', array('name' => 'frontend'));

$session = Mage::getSingleton('customer/session');           

//$customer = $session->getCustomer();
//$session->isLoggedIn()
//Zend_Debug::dump($customer->debug());</code></pre>

Please note that I have this working on a local instance of Magento CE 1.9.0.1, behind a domain like <em>thebooks.loc</em>.

If you are logged into Magento, but the code above returns false when you do $session->isLoggedIn(), then chances are that you haven't cleared your cookies and sessions, so don't go hacking Mage_Core_Model_Session_Abstract_Varien.

<h3>Layout & Block object</h3>

Why do we need layout object? Depends on the level of integration you plan on doing. Its nice to know that you can use the Magento layout to handle "partials". Partial being a fragment of a page you want to fetch and output in your other system. For example, how cool is being able to pull entire content area of checkout cart page, or recently viewed products block into your external system. And all of this is (more or less) doable by using the layout object.

Below is an example of fetching the top navigation menu (the one with Log In / Log Out links).

<pre><code class="language-php">require_once './shop/app/Mage.php';

umask(0);

Mage::init();

Mage::getSingleton('core/session', array('name' => 'frontend'));

$session = Mage::getSingleton('customer/session');           

$layout = Mage::app()->getLayout();
$layout->getUpdate()->addHandle('default');

if ($session->isLoggedIn()) {
    $layout->getUpdate()->addHandle('customer_logged_in');    
} else {
    $layout->getUpdate()->addHandle('customer_logged_out');
}

$layout->getUpdate()->load();

$layout->generateXml()
       ->generateBlocks();

$html = $layout->getBlock('top.links')->toHtml();

echo $html;</code></pre>

Which results in following.

<a href="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/snap_2014.05.30_08h20m15s_035_.png"><img src="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/snap_2014.05.30_08h20m15s_035_.png" alt="snap_2014.05.30_08h20m15s_035_" width="138" height="134" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-635" /></a> <a href="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/snap_2014.05.30_08h18m00s_034_.png"><img src="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/snap_2014.05.30_08h18m00s_034_.png" alt="snap_2014.05.30_08h18m00s_034_" width="192" height="120" class="alignnone size-large wp-image-636" /></a>

Further, you can (<em>theoretically</em> at least) simulate individual controller actions. For example, you can externally load entire product view page for a product with certain ID, or SKU value. How? Easy, just "copy-paste" the proper small portion of code from Mage_Catalog_ProductController (viewAction) into your external file, then call the proper layout handle and output the <em>content</em> block.

Hope this helps.

