item.content:encoded:
The lorempixel.com is a nice web service for providing "test" images that you can use in your test projects, etc. Images are provided under the creative commons license. Fetching a single image from a web service is simple as opening http://lorempixel.com/800/600/ url in your browser.<!--more-->

For the purposes of fetching several images in bulk, here is a little PHP script that might help out.

<pre><code class="language-php">//Bulk fetching images from lorempixel.com

$imageFolderPath = 'C:/tmp/images/';
$bulkSize = 500;

set_time_limit(0);
ini_set('memory_limit', '2048M');

for ($i=1; $i<=$bulkSize; $i++) {
    $options = array(
        CURLOPT_FILE    => fopen($imageFolderPath.$i.'.jpg', 'wb'),
        CURLOPT_TIMEOUT =>  60, // set this to 8 hours so we dont timeout on big files
        CURLOPT_URL     => 'http://lorempixel.com/800/600/',
    );

    $ch = curl_init();
    curl_setopt_array($ch, $options);
    curl_exec($ch);    

    if (curl_exec($ch) === false) {
        echo sprintf('%s loop error: %s%s', number_format($i), curl_error($ch), PHP_EOL);
    } else {
        echo sprintf('%s loop OK%s', number_format($i), PHP_EOL);
    }    
    curl_close($ch);    
}</code></pre>

Hope it helps.

Surprisingly, Elasticsearch (version at the time of this writing: 1.3.0) does not have a native bulk CSV importer. It does have a so called <em>bulk API</em> that makes it possible to perform many index/delete operations in a single API call. If you Google (search) for "elasticsearch csv import" chances are you will find "<em>CSV River Plugin (by Martin Bednar)</em>" first on the result list, so I encourage you to take a look at it as well. In this script, assumption is that you have a CSV file that you would like to convert to Elasticsearch type of JSON requests, then use curl to push that json file to Elasticsearch server.<!--more-->

Following script will convert CSV file to Elasticsearch index requests JSON file.

<pre><code class="language-php">if(php_sapi_name() != 'cli' && !empty($_SERVER['REMOTE_ADDR'])) {
	exit('Only shell execution execution is allowed!');
}

$csv = $argv[1]; /* Full absolute path to CSV file */
$_index = $argv[2]; /* Index */
$_type = $argv[3]; /* Index type */
$_id = $argv[4]; /* CSV column to use for ID */

if (file_exists($path=realpath(dirname(__FILE__) . '/'.$csv))) {
	$csv = $path;
} elseif (file_exists($path=realpath($csv))) {
	$csv = $path;
} else {
	exit('Unable to find CSV file at provided path!');
}

$csv_fp = fopen($csv, 'r');
$csv_columns = fgetcsv($csv_fp);

if (empty($csv_columns)) {
	fclose($csv_fp);
	exit('CSV file does not contain any headers!');
} else {
	$index_id = array_search($_id, $csv_columns);
}


$requests = $csv.'.requests.json';

if (file_exists($requests)) {
	fclose($csv_fp);
	exit(sprintf('Please remove/rename %s before proceeding!', $requests));	
}

$requests_fp = fopen($requests, 'w');

while (($entity = fgetcsv($csv_fp)) !== FALSE) {
	fwrite($requests_fp, sprintf('{ "index" : { "_index" : "%s", "_type" : "%s", "_id" : "%s" } }%s', $_index, $_type, $entity[$index_id], PHP_EOL));
	fwrite($requests_fp, json_encode((object)array_combine($csv_columns, $entity)).PHP_EOL);	
}

fclose($requests_fp);
fclose($csv_fp);

exit('All done...');</code></pre>

Please note, and feel free to change, that the script expects four parameter values to be passed to it (Full absolute path to CSV file, Index , Index type, CSV column to use for ID).

Once you have your CSV file converted to lets say requests.json you can execute following command to (import) index data into Elasticsearch :

<strong>curl -s -XPOST localhost:9200/_bulk --data-binary @requests.json</strong>

Hope it helps.

Recently I've been playing with the brand new toys, called the ELK stack. I am sure most of you reading this article have heard about it by now. Elasticsearch is developer friendly (think json & REST), open source, distributed, real-time search and analytics engine. Powered by Apache, the high-performance, full-featured text search engine library. You can think of Elasticsearch as being the same product as Apache Solr, its competitor. If you haven't already, I encourage you to try both, as I hate to say in this case, one is better than another. They are both great platforms, it is just that personally I like the Elasticsearch approach far more better.<!--more-->

Aside from Elasticsearch, there is this thing called Logstash. In essence logstash is a tool for managing events and logs. This management is done by routing input through some filter onto output. Given that this article is about managing your Magento logs, just imagine this as taking Magento's system.log file into logstash, applying some filters, which break/extract content from system.log into meaningful objects/messages and passes them onto output. Now imagine further that this output is Elasticsearch. With just a few lines of Logstash configuration you can achieve this powerful functionality, with zero coding.

Finally, we have Kibana, highly scalable "analyze & visualize" your data platform, JavaScript application that you run on your own server.

From business side of things, what is really nice about ELK stack is that its development is run under the same umbrella, that is Elasticsearch BV company. The company was founded in 2012 by the people behind Elasticsearch and Apache Lucene. They are offering training, dev support and production support.

Right, let us now focus back to Magento and parsing the logs.

First, we need to download and install <a href="http://logstash.net/">logstash</a>. You can find the quick instructions <a href="http://logstash.net/docs/1.4.2/tutorials/getting-started-with-logstash">here</a>.

It all comes down to running: bin/logstash -f my-config-file.conf.

To specifically parse Magento log file, you can use config like my-config-file.conf:

<pre><code class="language-txt">input {
    file {
		type => "magento"
		path => "C:/Bitnami/wampstack-5.4.30-0/apps/magento1901/htdocs/var/log/*.log"
		codec => multiline {
			pattern => "^%{TIMESTAMP_ISO8601} "
			negate => true
			what => "previous"
		}			
    }
}

filter {
	grok {
		match => ["message", "(?m)%{TIMESTAMP_ISO8601:triggered_at} %{LOGLEVEL:level} %{DATA:level_id} %{GREEDYDATA:message}"]
		remove_field => ["level_id"]
		overwrite => [ "message" ]
	}
	mutate {
		strip => "message"
	}  
}

output {
	elasticsearch {
		host => localhost
	}

}</code></pre>

As you can see above, content of config comes down to three main areas (input, filter, output). If you now quickly open a <a href="http://logstash.net/docs/1.4.2/">this page</a>, you can see how the page is divided nicely into four sections: inputs, codecs, filters, outputs. As you can quickly conclude, input can be set to grab the data from files, system log, redis, sqlite, s3 and large number of other sources. In our case, for parsing Magento logs, we have defined <i>file</i> input. If you look into the documentation for <a href="http://logstash.net/docs/1.4.2/inputs/file"><i>file</i></a> input, you will see that one of the params it accepts is <i>codec</i>.

Same as with inputs, there is a large number of predefined codecs you can use. Given that Magento logs are usually single line, but can be multiline (especially exception.log which throws trace of exception), we have defined <i>multiline</i> codec in our config. So how do we figure out what is a new line in our log files? Should be simply, in most cases, since Magento defines its log entries with special format that goes like "{time} {level} {level id}: {data}", so ideally each new log entry has the same ISO8601 date format. Thus, our <i>multiline</i> codec <i>pattern</i> parameter has been defined as "^%{TIMESTAMP_ISO8601} ". Please be sure to checkout the available options for this codec <a href="http://logstash.net/docs/1.4.2/codecs/multiline">here</a>.

Further, the filter section is what breaks the individual log entries into the objects/messages/entries you then pass along to output. This is a very powerful concept as it allows you to construct these objects/messages/entries to further suite your needs. For example you an add some new fields, which might be comprised of 1-2-... other fields, you can remove some fields, etc. In our example, are using the <i>grok</i> filter. Grok is currently the best way in logstash to parse unstructured log data into something structured and queryable. This might sound a bit confusing, since we just said that Magento logs are structured like "{time} {level} {level id}: {data}". However, that {data} in Magento log can be really anything.

The <i>output</i> part of config is defined to use Elasticsearch. See <a href="http://logstash.net/docs/1.4.2/outputs/elasticsearch">here</a> for more info on <i>elasticsearch</i> output parameters.

Once logstash is configured and run, you should be able to see your Magento logs being pulled into Elasticsearch, as shown below.

<a href="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/elasticsearch-magento.png"><img src="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/elasticsearch-magento-1024x483.png" alt="elasticsearch-magento" width="604" height="284" class="alignnone size-large wp-image-661" /></a>

Finally, downloaded and set Kibana, you should be able to see your log messages as shown below.

<a href="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/kibana1.png"><img src="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/kibana1-1024x489.png" alt="kibana1" width="604" height="288" class="alignnone size-large wp-image-663" /></a>

<a href="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/kibana2.png"><img src="http://foggyline.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/kibana2-1024x489.png" alt="kibana2" width="604" height="288" class="alignnone size-large wp-image-662" /></a>

Ideally, you would further extract the log file name as additional field during the filtering process, so you can use it within Kibana to further filter your data by that value as well.

To conclude, the ELK stack seems pretty neat to me. Prime reason is that everything is so simple, from Elasticsearch, Logstash to Kibana. You don't need any complex installations, etc. It all just works out of the box. Pretty positive I'll start using it for some of the production stuff.

Hope this helps.
